set.seed(80135)

Define and plot the custom posterior

cpost <- function(x) {return(0.5*exp(-0.5*(x-3)**2)+0.5*exp(-0.5*(x+3)**2))}
p <- seq(-8,8,0.001)
y <- cpost(p)
td <- dnorm(p,0,1)
df <- data.frame(p,y,td)
(plt <- ggplot(df)+geom_line(aes(p,y), color="brown3", lwd=0.8)+geom_line(aes(p,td), linetype="dashed", color="deeppink3", lwd=0.8))

Define function for MCMC

MCMC <- function(post, sigma, Nit, lowlim, highlim) {
  x <- runif(Nit,lowlim,highlim)
  sample <- post(x)
  dens <- rnorm(Nit,0,sigma)
  chain <- rep(0,Nit)
  ar <- Nit
    for (i in seq(1,length(sample)-1)) {
      
      targp <- (sample[i+1]/sample[i])*(dens[i+1]/dens[i])
      
      if (targp < 1) {
        extraction <- runif(1,0,1)
        if (extraction < targp) {
          chain[i] <- x[i+1]
        }
        else {
          chain[i] <- x[i]
          x[i+1] <- x[i]
          sample[i+1] <- sample[i]
          dens[i+1] <- dens[i]
          ar <- ar -1
        }
      }
      else {
        chain[i] <- x[i+1]
      }
    }
  acc_rate <- ar/Nit
  
  MCres <- list("chain"=chain, "acc_rt"=acc_rate)
  return(MCres)
}
MC <- MCMC(cpost,1,1000000,-10,10)
chain <- data.frame(MC$chain)
colnames(chain) <- "Counts"

Thinning and burn-in

Two other relevant parameters for optimizing a MCMC algorithm are the burn-in, meaning the number of steps ignored by the sampling at the beginning and the thinning, meaning the number of steps between two samplings. To provide concise results I will repackage the whole analysis done above into a single function and provide only the relevant plots and quantities

parest <- function(burn_in,thinning,chain) {

  p <- seq(-8,8,0.001)
  y <- cpost(p)
  td <- dnorm(p,0,1)
  df <- data.frame(p,y,td)
  
  #remove first burn in rows
  chain <- chain[-(1:burn_in)]
  #remove rows at thinning rate
  chain <- chain[seq(1,length(chain),thinning)]
  
  chain <- data.frame(chain)
  colnames(chain) <- "Counts"
  
  c.MC <- as.mcmc(chain)
  lgs <- seq(0,75,5)
  acf <- autocorr(c.MC,lgs)
  efs <- floor(effectiveSize(c.MC))
  label <- paste("Effective size:",efs)
  dat <- data.frame(lgs,acf)
  
  p1 <- ggplot() + geom_line(data = df, aes(p,y/2.5), color="brown3", linetype="dashed", lwd=0.7) + geom_histogram(data = chain, aes(Counts,after_stat(density)), binwidth=0.3, fill="orangered", color="ivory")
#posterior and density estimate rescaled for graphical purposes
  
  p2 <- ggplot(dat)+geom_line(aes(lgs,acf), lwd=1, linetype="dotted", color="plum3")+geom_point(aes(lgs,acf), size=3, shape=9, color="purple2")+ labs(x="steps", y="ACF") + annotate(geom="text", x=35, y=0.6, label=label)
  
  plt <- ggarrange(p1,p2, nrow = 1, ncol = 2)
  return(plt)
}
(parest(1000,10,MC$chain))

(parest(1000,20,MC$chain))

(parest(1000,5,MC$chain))

Thinning = 10 seems to be a good trade off between effective size of the sample and decorrelation between datapoints

Exercise 2

Following the general framework introduced during class we can sum everything up in a couple of functions

efficacy_analysis <- function(tot_vaccine, tot_placebo, pos_vaccine, pos_placebo){
        
    patient <- c(rep(" Vaccine ", tot_vaccine ),
    rep(" Placebo ", tot_placebo ))
    tested <- c(rep("Pos", pos_vaccine ),
    rep("Neg", tot_vaccine - pos_vaccine ),
    rep("Pos", pos_placebo ),
    rep("Neg", tot_placebo - pos_placebo ))
    vax.tb <- tibble( tested = tested , patient = patient )
    table( vax.tb[[2]], vax.tb[[1]])

    modelString <- "
    model {
    for ( i in 1:Ntot ) {
    tested[i] ~ dbern( theta[ patient [i]] )
    }
    for ( k in 1: Nclass ) {
    theta[k] ~ dbeta(3 , 100)
    }
    }"

    dataList = list(
        tested = ifelse(vax.tb$tested == "Neg", 0, 1),
        patient = as.integer ( factor(vax.tb$patient )),
        Ntot = nrow(vax.tb) ,
        Nclass = nlevels (factor( vax.tb$patient )) )
    
    vax_chains <- run.jags( modelString ,
                            sample = 15000,
                            n.chains = 4,
                            method = "parallel",
                            monitor = "theta",
                            data = dataList);
                            

    summary (vax_chains)

    vax_res <- tidybayes :: tidy_draws(vax_chains ) |> select ('theta[1]':'theta[2]') |>
                                                       rename ( Placebo = 'theta[1]', Vaccine = 'theta[2]') |>
                                                       mutate (diff_rate = ( Placebo - Vaccine ) / Placebo * 100,
                                                               Placebo_perc = Placebo * 100,
                                                               Vaccine_perc = Vaccine * 100)

    allmcmc2 <- as.mcmc(vax_res , vars="diff_rate")
    return(allmcmc2)
}
plotPosterior <- function(samples, ci_perc, color, title) {
  
    # Convert samples to numeric
    samples <- as.numeric(samples)
    df <- data.frame(samples)
  
    # Calculate credibility interval
    ci <- quantile(samples, probs = c((1-ci_perc)/2, 1-(1-ci_perc)/2))
    ci <- as.numeric(ci)
    
    results_df <- data.frame(
    Mean = format(mean(samples), digits = 3),
    Std = format(sd(samples), digits = 3),
    C.Interval = paste('min:',format(ci[1], digits = 3), '  ','max:' ,format(ci[2], digits = 3)) )
    
    # Plot the histogram
    plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x = samples)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, aes(y = after_stat(density)), fill = color, color = 'black') +
    labs(title = title, x = "Efficacy", y = "Frequency") +
    
    # Add credibility interval lines
    geom_segment(aes(x = ci[1], xend = ci[1], y = 0, yend = Inf), col = "black", lwd = 1) +
    geom_segment(aes(x = ci[2], xend = ci[2], y = 0, yend = Inf), col = "black", lwd = 1) +
    geom_segment(aes(x = mean(samples), xend = mean(samples), y = 0, yend = Inf), col = "red", lwd = 1)
    
    show(plot)
    results_df
}
